data.content:
In xUnit, there are no setup/teardown attributes. Here's the mapping:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` / `[TearDown]` | Constructor / `IDisposable` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` / `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` with a shared fixture |

```csharp
// Shared fixture replaces [OneTimeSetUp] / [OneTimeTearDown]
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp] — runs before each test
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture db)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // IDisposable replaces [TearDown] — runs after each test
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **Per-test setup** → constructor. xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**.
- **Per-test teardown** → `IDisposable.Dispose()`.
- **One-time setup/teardown** → extract into a fixture class implementing `IDisposable`, then apply `IClassFixture<T>`. The fixture is injected via the constructor and shared across all tests in the class.
- If you need to share the fixture across **multiple test classes**, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` with a `[Collection]` attribute instead.
